ce:section.ce:para:
The potential application of C-dots prepared from the upcycled plastic waste has been checked in fluorescence-based metal ion sensing (Fig. 6
                         (a–c)). For the experimentation, the fluorescence behavior of all the three P-CDs, C-CDs and B-CDs was checked against 13 different metal ions: Ni2+, Zn2+, Cd2+, Fe2+, K+, Cu2+, Ca2+, Hg2+, Na+, Pb2+, Co2+, Mg2+, Ba2+. All the three types of C-dots have displayed comparable variations to each type of chosen metal ion. The metal ions such as Ni2+, Zn2+, Cd2+, Fe2+, K+, Ca2+, Hg2+, Na+, Pb2+, Co2+, Mg2+ and Ba2+ has displayed very slight quenching of fluorescence emission intensity as compared to pure C-dots. Whereas, the strongest quenching of all the three types of C-dots was observed in presence of Cu2+ ion (Scheme 2
                        ). Since the highest quencher (Cu2+) is considered as one of the prime environmental contaminants in most of the water resources (Lva et al., 2019), therefore focus was given on investigating Cu2+ ion detection by using P-CDs, C-CDs and B-CDs.
